Even the Greek poets, free and spontaneous as they are, draw largely upon Ho- meric ideas, and even upon Homeric phrases : a Roman poet, who owed to Greece the whole awakening of his spiritual life, would have considered it little short of madness to desert the Greek models. The only great presentment of heroic times open to Virgil was that of the Homeric poemsÍ¾ it would have seemed impossible for him to cast his epic in any mould but in that of the Iliad and Odyssey. To reproduce their form in Roman outline, use their details, absorb their spirit, surpass if possible their effect, would be his first and most natural ambition.'
